0–1554":"1490–1554","1520–1576":"1520–1576","1470–1500":"1470–1500","1469–Female":"1469–Overleden","1572":"1572","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","before 1515":"vóór 1515","1525":"1525","1469":"1469","1500":"1500","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","about 1483":"circa 1483","1515":"1515","Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","South Duffield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"South Duffield, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1483–1525":"about 1483–1525","1483–1525":"1483–1525","1490–1550":"1490–1550","–1515":"–1515","1495–1572":"1495–1572","1490–1554":"1490–1554","1520–1576":"1520–1576","1470–1500":"1470–1500","1469–Female":"1469–Deceased","1572":"1572","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","before 1515":"before 1515","1525":"1525","1469":"1469","1500":"1500","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","about 1483":"about 1483","1515":"1515","Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","South Duffield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"South Duffield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Irish (Dublin and Cork), and Scottish: ethnic or habitational name applied either to a Scandinavian or to someone from Normandy in northern France. The Scandinavian adventurers of the Dark Ages called themselves <i>northmenn</i> ‘men from the North’. Before 1066, Scandinavian settlers in England were already fairly readily absorbed, and <i>Northman</i> and <i>Normann</i> came to be used as bynames and later as personal names, even among the Saxon inhabitants. The term gained a new use from 1066 onward, when England was settled by invaders from Normandy, who were likewise of Scandinavian origin but by now largely integrated with the native population and speaking a Romance language, retaining only their original ancient Germanic name.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Norman</i> (recorded in the late Old English period as <i>Northman</i>), derived from <i>northman</i> ‘northerner’.","Americanized form of German   Normann  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Normand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Andre, Laurent, Marcel, Pierre, Amie, Donat, Emile, Herve, Jacques, Jean Noel, Jean-Michel.","French and Breton (mainly Finistère; also <b>Le Normand</b>): habitational name for someone from Normandy, a region in northern France (see   Norman  ). Compare   Lenormand  .","Scottish (Fife): variant of   Norman  ."]},{"name":"Noorman","meanings":["Dutch: from <i>Noorman</i> ‘Northman’, ethnic name for a Norwegian. Compare   Norman  ."]},{"name":"Normann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.  German Gerd.","German: variant of   Nordmann  . This surname is also found in Denmark."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Norman was born about 1483, in York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, David Chaloner, was 14 and his mother, Annes verch Jenkyn, was 16. He had at least 1 daughter with Jane. He died in 1525, in South Duffield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1483–1525":"umbes 1483–1525","1483–1525":"1483–1525","1490–1550":"1490–1550","–1515":"–1515","1495–1572":"1495–1572","1490–1554":"1490–1554","1520–1576":"1520–1576","1470–1500":"1470–1500","1469–Female":"1469–Surnud","1572":"1572","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","before 1515":"enne 1515","1525":"1525","1469":"1469","1500":"1500","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","about 1483":"umbes 1483","1515":"1515","Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rickmansworth, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yo